05052nam a22007815i 9789048552870DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485528707 a10.1515/97890485528702doi  a(DE-B1597)642614  a(OCoLC)1371971660  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aDG975.B593 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a945.4108092223/eng/202303131 aBernhardt, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGenevra Sforza and the Bentivoglio :bFamily, Politics, Gender and Reputation in (and beyond) Renaissance Bologna /cElizabeth Bernhardt. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGendering the Late Medieval and Early Modern World00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIllustrations, Tables, Figures, and Documents -- tAbbreviations of Archives and Libraries -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1. Genevra Sforza de’ Bentivoglio (ca. 1441–1507) : Lost and Found in Renaissance Italy -- t2. Twice Bentivoglio: Genevra Sforza on the Marriage Market (1446–1454 and 1463–1464) -- t3. Genevra Sforza and Bentivoglio Family Strategies: Creating and Extending Kinship on a Massive Scale -- t4. Genevra Sforza in Her Own Words: Patron and Client Relationships from Her Correspondence -- t5. The Wheel of Fortune: Genevra Sforza and the Fall of the Bentivoglio (1506–1507) -- t6. Making and Dispelling Fake History: Genevra Sforza and Her ‘Black Legends’ (1506–present) -- tConclusions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGenevra Sforza (ca. 1441–1507) lived her long life near the apex of Italian Renaissance society as wife of two successive de facto rulers of Bologna: Sante then Giovanni II Bentivoglio. Placed twice there without a dowry by Duke Francesco Sforza as part of a larger Milanese plan, Genevra served her family by fulfilling the gendered role demanded of her by society, most notably by contributing eighteen children, accepting many illegitimates born to Giovanni II, and helping arrange their future alliances for the success of the family at large. Based on contemporary archival research conducted across Italy, this biography presents Genevra as the object of academic study for the first time. The book explores how Genevra’s life-story, filled with a multitude of successes appropriate for an elite fifteenth-century female, was transformed into a concordant body of misogynistic legends about how she destroyed the Bentivoglio and the city of Bologna.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aRenaissance Italy, Bentivoglio, Genevra Sforza, Women's History, Family History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cprintz978946372684940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048552870?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048552870423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048552870/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EB